  <scaffolding>
    <layer level="1" name="Layer 1">
      <focus/>
      <content>Define core terms: Need-to-know (access only for specific job duties); Least Privilege (minimum access overall); CIA Triad (Confidentiality protects data from unauthorized disclosure). Importance: Minimizes breach risk, enhances accountability, prevents insider threats. Example: In healthcare, nurses access only assigned patient charts.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="2" name="Layer 2">
      <focus/>
      <content>Relationships: Need-to-know operates within Access Control (post-authentication via Authorization); complements Segregation of Duties (no overlapping full access). Links to data lifecycle (classify data first). Tools overview: IAM systems enforce via policies.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="3" name="Layer 3">
      <focus/>
      <content>Steps: 1. Define roles/jobs; 2. Map permissions to specific needs (avoid broad access); 3. Implement RBAC (role-based) or ABAC (attribute-based); 4. Conduct regular audits/reviews and use JIT access. Tools: IAM (e.g., Okta, Azure AD), logging for accountability. Example: Annual access reviews revoke unused permissions.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="4" name="Layer 4">
      <focus/>
      <content>Connect to Zero Trust (continuous verification); Data Lifecycle Management (access tied to classification); Incident Response (audit trails for forensics). Optimization: JIT/PIM (privileged identity management). Real-world: GSA guidelines enforce in federal systems to improve accountability and reduce misuse.</content>
    </layer>
  </scaffolding>
